        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-07-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-07-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="158"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d158">
                <head>158. Memorandum by the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>)<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d158fn1">Source: National Security Council, Secretariat, Directives,
                        1971, Directive #89. Confidential. A copy was sent to <persName
                            corresp="#p_MTH1">Moorer</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-07-20">July 20, 1971</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list>
                    <head>MEMORANDUM FOR</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                    <item>The Director of Central Intelligence</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President has directed that Departments and Agencies concerned refrain from
                    commenting on the implications of his July 15, 1971 announcement concerning the
                    People’s Republic of China.<note n="2" xml:id="d158fn2">For text of the
                        President’s remarks to the nation announcing acceptance of an invitation to
                        visit the People’s Republic of China, see <hi rend="italic">Public Papers:
                            Nixon, 1971</hi>, pp. 819–820. Nixon visited the People’s Public of
                        China February 21–28, 1972.</note> This directive applies to both on the
                    record and background statements as <pb facs="0359" n="328" xml:id="pg_328"/>
                    well as to inquiries within official and diplomatic channels. In those instances
                    where it is considered that substantive statements must be made, he has asked
                    that such statements be cleared with him through the office of the Assistant to
                    the President for National Security Affairs.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry A. Kissinger</persName>
                        <note n="3" xml:id="d158fn3">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
